PNA ) , but it=E2=80=99s worth diving further into the specifics of how App=
le Intelligence works. This visualization from WWDC=E2=80=99s Platforms Sta=
te of the Union presentation ( https://developer.apple.com/videos/play/wwdc=
2024/102/?time=3D95 ) is a great place to start:

Apple Intelligence Infrastructure ( https://machinelearning.apple.com/resea=
rch/introducing-apple-foundation-models )

Start with the on-device model: the language model is ~3 billion parameters=
; the memory requirements for a model are, as a rule of thumb, 2GB of memor=
y for every 1 billion parameters. That would mean that the on-device model =
requires 6GB of memory. However, Apple says that it has compressed the mode=
l such that it requires around 3.5 bits-per-weight (as opposed to 16-bit), =
which would imply that loading the model only takes around 3GB of memory. T=
hat is both impressive, and also explains why 8GB is the minimum amount of =
RAM on which these models will run (you still need memory to actually run t=
he OS and attendant apps).

Apple is manifesting the model=E2=80=99s capabilities via adapters, the nam=
e of which comes from the technique used to create them: =E2=80=9CLow-Rank =
Adaptation=E2=80=9D, more commonly referred to as LoRA. This entails traini=
ng the model on specific use cases, and loading the appropriate layers as n=
ecessary, to maximize the model=E2=80=99s capabilities in those use cases. =
In this case the use cases are:

* Summarization
* Proofreading
* Mail replies
* Tone adjustment
* Refining
* Query Handling
* Friendly
* Urgency

I=E2=80=99m not entirely clear what =E2=80=9CFriendly=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9CUrgency=E2=80=9D mean, but the other categories are self-explanatory, an=
d speak to both the relatively limited capability of these models, and at t=
he same time Apple=E2=80=99s focus on actually delivering functionality tha=
t is useful (and, as I noted yesterday, leaving it up to Aggregated supplie=
rs to do the complex stuff).

The semantic index is basically a highly optimized database of all of your =
information; that information is collected via the same APIs that power Spo=
tlight, Apple=E2=80=99s system-wide search functionality (this means that t=
he extent to which Apple can utilize information in 3rd-party apps is depen=
dent on the degree to which those apps have fully integrated the various Sp=
otlight APIs). The local model incorporates this information via Retrieval-=
Augmented Generation, more commonly referred to as RAG. The way RAG works i=
s that a query prompts a search of the semantic index for the relevant info=
rmation; that information is then encoded into a second query that includes=
 the original request and the relevant information, which generates a respo=
nse.

A key limitation of RAG is the size of the context window, i.e. how long th=
e query can be. Larger context windows are both slower and require more mem=
ory (the necessary amount of memory increases quadratically with context wi=
ndow length). Apple did not say how large the context window is for the on-=
device model, but I would imagine that this is a key determinant of when qu=
eries are ultimately answered by the on-device model versus the model in th=
e cloud.

Apple did not say how big that cloud model is, simply referring to it as =
=E2=80=9Ca larger server-based language model=E2=80=9D. I have some theorie=
s, though:

* First, contra the upcoming episode of Sharp Tech, I now think that privat=
e cloud computing is in fact entirely Apple chips. The other blog post ( ht=
tps://security.apple.com/blog/private-cloud-compute/ ) about private cloud =
computing that I linked to yesterday spends a significant amount of time ex=
plaining the end-to-end security environment that is created to host these =
requests, and which is dependent on various features of Apple Silicon.
* Second, developing new chips requires a substantial amount of lead time, =
on the order of years; I don=E2=80=99t see any evidence that Apple was so f=
orward thinking as to have been developing server-specific chips optimized =
for AI inference on that sort of timeline (particularly given that a chunk =
of their chip team left to found Nuvia to make the server chips that Apple =
didn=E2=80=99t want to).
* The third point builds on the second: I assume that the Apple chips in Pr=
ivate Cloud Computing are M2 Ultra chips, which max out with 192 GB of RAM;=
 using the rule of thumb I noted above, this suggests that the cloud model =
is probably around 70 billion parameters, or perhaps a bit larger, with wha=
t I expect is a fairly large context window. This would fit comfortably int=
o memory on a single chip and, based on the published performance of other =
70 billion parameter models, provide the performance Apple advertises, i.e.=
 somewhere between GPT-3.5-Turbo and GPT-4-Turbo.

With regards to that last point, my reading of the security entailed in Pri=
vate Cloud Computing is that a user=E2=80=99s device establishes a temporar=
y 1-to-1 connection with a server in the cloud (which again, I think is one=
 chip); this is obviously a sizable investment on Apple=E2=80=99s part, par=
ticularly given that using Apple Intelligence is free, but these chips are =
used across users, who are invoking them infrequently. In short, I think th=
e cost is likely reasonable, particularly since M2 Ultras cost a lot less t=
han Nvidia GPUs!

The other piece of this illustration to call out is the =E2=80=9CApp Intent=
s Toolbox=E2=80=9D; this is the list of developer-defined actions exposed b=
y apps to the operating system. To date app intents have been utilized for =
Siri, Shortcuts, and Spotlight; going forward app intents will be leveraged=
 by Apple Intelligence to accomplish tasks across apps, again via RAG.

What is fascinating to consider is the extent to which these intents might =
be a Faustian bargain for developers: the implication of exposing functiona=
lity to Apple Intelligence is that the user interface of an app is diminish=
ed in importance; this is fine for apps that have differentiated resources =
that are not dependent on owning the user interface, but it does provide a =
long-run existential risk to apps that rely on user attention (in the most =
obvious use case, to show ads). The power of an Aggregator, though, is to c=
ompel suppliers like app developers to deliver functionality on their terms=
, so to the extent that Apple Intelligence becomes a meaningful interface f=
or accomplishing things on your phone, is the extent to which developers wi=
ll have to run the risk of losing user attention even as they deliver user =
benefits.

The final thing to notice is what is not on this graph: ChatGPT. Basically,=
 when Apple Intelligence decides it cannot fulfill a user request =E2=80=94=
 which I expect it to do fairly aggressively in the interest of avoiding ha=
llucinations =E2=80=94 it will offer to kick the request to ChatGPT, or wha=
tever other model is plugged into the interface that Apple is building for =
3rd-parties.

This is, all things considered, a valuable position to be in for OpenAI, bu=
t it=E2=80=99s also hardly ideal; the analogy I am thinking of is Amazon=E2=
=80=99s logistics service: the e-commerce company has been building out the=
 capabilities to make its own deliveries to the vast majority of the popula=
tion, and then leverages 3rd-party delivery services like UPS or Fedex or U=
SPS for the deliveries that it can=E2=80=99t do cost-effectively. That=E2=
=80=99s great for Amazon, but not so great for the 3rd-parties, and yet the=
 volume is such that they still take it on.

Apple=E2=80=99s AI Bear Case
--------------------

I obviously am very optimistic about Apple=E2=80=99s chances in winning in =
AI, both before the WWDC keynote ( https://stratechery.com/2024/apple-intel=
ligence-is-right-on-time/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cm=
